Let’s talk a minute about programming. First video is Marissa’s third attempt at her meet in September - 107.5kg/237lbs. Second video is from last night. She worked up to a triple at 8 rpe of 240lbs! 

Over the last few months she hasn’t done any real competition squats. 
She’s had moderate volume with SSB’s, Pin squats and 1.5 squats. 
These variations aren’t what social media wants to see (no one wants to the see the work, just the big numbers). I see too many lifters get bored after 2-3 weeks and go off program.  This leads to a never ending cycle and it’s hard to make real progress. 

Marissa stuck to her program week after week and is now reaping the benefits. She’s on track to break a couple of the @usaplga 67.5kg state records 👏🏼👏🏼

This is your reminder to trust the process and your numbers will come.

Working with Erin is such a learning experience for me.  I’ve had to think outside of the box not just for training progression but also with cueing. 

Here she’s doing TRX assisted squats to a foam roller. 
Using the foam roller allowed her be able to still physically feel the touch of squatting deeper but not allow her to plop down. 

The TRX gave her the little bit of comfort knowing she won’t fall down (she’s not really using it pull herself up, just for balance when she needs it.)

Our AMAZING Erin has progressed to supported squats WITHOUT A BOX!! This is massive for Erin. 

Erin has cerebral palsy and when we started working together she struggled a lot with normal, everyday movements let alone exercise. 

She has gained so much bodily control, balance, self awareness and most importantly, confidence! Erin will go around tell everyone in class that she’s a bad ass (she is!). 

I’m excited to see what the next few months of training bring.

New year and new appreciation and approach to training. 
I’m taking the advice I give most of my lifters. Be intentional with every rep. Slow down and do it right. 

I’m making sure I brace before every rep and I do it properly.  I *thought* I was breathing and bracing properly but I wasn’t. I was breathing into my chest and not my belly. My pelvic floor PT said it’s very common with #postpartum. 

The road to a 600lb deadlift continues. Let’s go! 

#pelvicfloorphysicaltherapy #girlswholift #girlswhopowerlift #usapl #usapowerlifting #usaplga #grrrl #fatathlete #plussizepower #squats #quads #glutes

This week Erin worked on becoming more independent by listening and following directions.
 I had her do her deadlifts without me standing there moving her hands, feet, etc. instead I had her listen to my instructions and then do what I tell her to do. 

This was a fantastic critical thinking exercise and gave her more confidence with the barbell.

Life’s a little different right now. I’m 5 days post microdiscectomy and laminectmy at L4-L5. 

I have to use a walker if I’m walking more than a couple of feet at time and I’m not allowed to bend, twist or lift anything heavier than 10lbs for 12 weeks. 
This definitely wasn’t how I expected to spend my summer, but I’m thankful to not be in anymore pain and able to walk again.

It’s been 8 weeks since I had the worst pain of my life that left me unable to move to the point where EMS had to come and get me off the floor after I had been there for 8 hours. 
I had emergency spinal surgery to remove a massive bulging disc with severe stenosis that lead to acute onset of  cauda equina syndrome when I tried to change the laundry around. 
I spent 7 days in the hospital, 4 of which I couldn’t walk or relieve my bladder without a catheter. 

I still have some nerve issues that are causing heel drop that gets worse with prolonged walking and I have some tingling/pins and needles in my foot, but I’m up and walking and I don’t have 10/10 constant pain. 

These assisted bodyweight squats are the first step to me getting back to a “normal” life.
